{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567715"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.16,0.31,0.44,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82483"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1218"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"1818"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2816"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82483"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of fatigue, weight loss, and intermittent dizziness. She also reports arm pain when writing or typing. She recently was diagnosed with pyoderma gangrenosum on her lower leg, and has multiple erythematous nodules on her anterior shins which are tender but awaiting biopsy results. She noticed a new ulcer on her upper arm in the last 3 weeks which has not healed.  She was previously well and takes no regular medications. She works as an administrative assistant.  She denies any trauma or substance use. She recently had a thorough sexually transmitted infection screen which was negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure is 145/90 mmHg in the right arm and 110/70 mmHg in the left arm, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The left radial and brachial pulses are weak compared to the right side. There is a bruit audible over the left subclavian artery. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Giant cell arteritis","Thoracic outlet syndrome","Polyarteritis nodosa","Takayasu\u0027s arteritis","Fibromuscular dysplasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of Takayasu\u0027s arteritis, including constitutional symptoms (fatigue, weight loss), vascular insufficiency symptoms (arm pain with use), and characteristic examination findings (blood pressure discrepancy between arms, diminished pulses, and arterial bruit). Dermatological manifestations of Takayasu\u0027s arteritis include pyoderma gangrenosum, erythema nodosum and non-healing ulcers which are present in this patient.  Treatment is focused on reducing active inflammation with prednisolone as first-line, with consideration of methotrexate or azathioprine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETakayasu\u0027s arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic large vessel vasculitis that typically affects young women in their second and third decade and the cause is unknown. It primarily affects the aorta and its major branches, leading to stenosis, occlusion, or aneurysm formation. The disease often presents with a systemic inflammatory phase  (\u0027prepulseless stage\u0027) followed by a vascular phase (\u0027pulseless stage\u0027)with symptoms of end-organ ischemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects individuals over 50 years of age and has a predilection for the temporal arteries. While it can affect the aorta and its branches, the age of presentation and absence of temporal artery symptoms make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyarteritis nodosa\u003C/strong\u003E is a medium vessel vasculitis that typically presents with multisystem involvement including skin lesions, peripheral neuropathy, and renal involvement. The pattern of large vessel involvement seen here is not typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibromuscular dysplasia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause arterial stenosis but typically affects renal and carotid arteries, and is not associated with systemic inflammation or elevated inflammatory markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThoracic outlet syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause upper limb symptoms but would not explain the systemic symptoms, elevated inflammatory markers, or blood pressure discrepancy between arms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Takayasu\u0027s arteritis typically affects young women under 40 years of age and presents with non-specific constitutional symptoms and vascular insufficiency.","Characteristic findings ofTakayasu\u0027s arteritis  include diminished or absent peripheral pulses and blood pressure differences between arms."],"references":["Setty HS et al. Takayasu\u0027s arteritis - a comprehensive review. In Journal of Rare Diseases Research \u0026 Treatment (Online). 2007.  Available at: https://www.rarediseasesjournal.com/articles/takayasus-arteritis--a-comprehensive-review.html","Zhang X, Jiao Y. Takayasu arteritis with pyoderma gangrenosum: case reports and literature review.  BMC Rhematology. 2019: 45.  Available at: https://bmcrheumatol.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s41927-019-0098-z"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19275"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T19:03:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T19:04:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12009"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82483"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.e